result.execSummary:
The defendant Jose Rafael Munoz Jr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jose Rafael Munoz in court.  Patrick D. Winter appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
cab
  DOC agent also in court.
Defendant is to be on a payment plan.  If he misses once, the agent is to contact the court for a review date.
Based upon the defendant's compliance with the conditions of probation, the Court ordered that time in the House of Correction, which was ordered as a condition of probation but stayed to today's date, be stayed for use at the agent's discretion in the future.

Defendant Jose Rafael Munoz in court with attorney Thomas K. Hackbart.  Owen M. Piotrowski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing Proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant.
AS TO COUNT 3
The court sentenced the defendant to 80 DAYS in the House of Correction, consecutive to each other and any other sentence, with credit for 3 DAYS time served, with Huber.  Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 18 MONTHS.

AS TO COUNT 4
The court sentenced the defendant to 80 DAYS in the House of Correction, consecutive to each other and any other sentence, with Huber.  Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 18 MONTHS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION
-Serve 30 DAYS (as to each count) as Condition Time, STAYED pending review.
-Batterers Intervention program, or a course in anger management.
-Parenting classes.
-Absolute sobriety, random urine screens.
-Treatment and/or counseling as determined by agent.
-No VIOLENT contact with victim.
-Obtain/maintain employment.
-No contact with firearms.
-Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA & DV surcharges during period of probation, failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. 
-Court WAIVED all NON-Mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay.

*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a crime of domestic violence.
*Court GRANTED Expungement after successful completion of all terms of probation, payment of all ordered costs, and no new law violations.
